   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Defining a Potential"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We use a class based approach to defining our potentials.\n",
    "\n",
    "Theres a base class called JaxDensity where all of the numerical methods are defined.\n",
    "Specific sublasses corresponding to known models (e.g Plummer NFW) are defined for each model in models.py\n",
    "\n",
    "You can look at {doc}`./tutorial_potential` for some examples of the built-in models.\n",
    "\n",
    "For the built-in models if an analytical espressions for dynamical quantities are known, the analytical espressions are used, if not the numerical methods from the base class are used.\n",
    "\n",
    "For testing purposes it maybe useful to compare the numerical methods to the analytical methods to see if they're working correctly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "tags": [
     "hide-cell"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%load_ext autoreload\n",
    "%autoreload 2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from dynamicAll.base import JaxDensity"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The general idea if you want to implement a model that is not built in is that all you have to define is one or two functions and then everything else can be calculated numerically.\n",
    "\n",
    "The more functions you specify will lead to slightly faster calculations and perhaps slighly more accurate results, but we show that even defining just one function you can achieve good results.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll start with the Plummer model as an example.\n",
    "\n",
    "A particularly tricky function to calculate given just a density profile is the Distribution function. This is a function that gives the probability of finding a star with a given energy at a given position. It is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "f(\\mathcal{E}) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{8}\\pi^2} \\frac{d}{d\\mathcal{E}}\\int_0^{\\mathcal{E}}\\frac{d\\rho}{d\\psi}\\frac{d\\psi}{\\sqrt{\\mathcal{E}-\\psi}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The combination of integrals and derivatives can make this a difficult function to calculate. Below we show how we can calculate this function for the Plummer model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from functools import partial\n",
    "import jax\n",
    "import jax.numpy as jnp\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class Plummer_test(JaxDensity):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, M: float, rs: float):\n",
    "        self._M = M\n",
    "        self._rs = rs\n",
    "        self._params = {\"M\": self._M, \"rs\": self._rs}\n",
    "\n",
    "    @classmethod\n",
    "    @partial(jax.jit, static_argnums=(0,))\n",
    "    def _density(cls, r: jnp.ndarray, params) -> jnp.ndarray:\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        Parameters\n",
    "        ----------\n",
    "        r : np.ndarray\n",
    "            radius : np.sqrt(x**2+y**2 + z**2)\n",
    "        M : float\n",
    "            _description_\n",
    "        a : float\n",
    "            _description_\n",
    "\n",
    "        Returns\n",
    "        -------\n",
    "        np.ndarray\n",
    "            _description_\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        q = r / params[\"rs\"]\n",
    "        coeff = 3 * params[\"M\"] / (4 * jnp.pi * params[\"rs\"] ** 3)\n",
    "\n",
    "        return coeff * (1 + q**2) ** (-5 / 2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we defined a plummer model using the density as a starting point. If we wanted a different starting point -i.e you have a specific parameterization in mind for the mass or potential - you can instead use JaxMass or JaxPotential as the starting point.\n",
    "\n",
    "In that case all you need to define is _mass and _density and everything else can be done numerically.\n",
    "\n",
    "You can start out with a Distribution function, but in that case you also need to specify the potential in the currrent  implementation. See the Docs and source code doc strings for more information."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Initialisation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "params = {\"M\": 3e5, \"rs\": 0.5}\n",
    "plum_test = Plummer_test(**params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "```{note}\n",
    "    You don't have to initialize the class. You can use it in a more functional form by using the class methods.\n",
    "\n",
    "    all that calling plum_test.density(r) does is call the class method _density(r,params). In actual fitting where you're changing the parameters you would always want to use the class methods rather than the instance methods.\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "r = jnp.logspace(-2, 2, 100)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "lw = 3\n",
    "## instance method\n",
    "ax.plot(r, plum_test.density(r), lw=lw)\n",
    "## class method\n",
    "ax.plot(r, Plummer_test._density(r, params), linestyle=\"--\", lw=lw)\n",
    "ax.set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"r [kpc]\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$\\rho$ [M$_{\\odot}$ kpc$^{-3}$]\",\n",
    ");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Test against built-in Model\n",
    "The built in Plummer model has almost all dynamical quantites in analytical form. \n",
    "We'll use them to test the numerical methods."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from dynamicAll import models\n",
    "\n",
    "plum = models.Plummer(**params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[None, None, Text(0.5, 0, 'r'), Text(0, 0.5, '$\\\\Delta \\\\Phi$'), (1e-20, 0.01)]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1600x500 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "vec_mass = jax.vmap(plum_test._mass, in_axes=(0, None))\n",
    "# vec_mass2 = jax.vmap(plum_test.test_mass, in_axes=(0, None))\n",
    "r = jnp.logspace(-10, 2, 100)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, figsize=(16, 5))\n",
    "lw = 3\n",
    "# plot difference between the two mass functions\n",
    "ax[0].plot(r, jnp.abs(vec_mass(r, params) - plum.mass(r)), lw=lw)\n",
    "\n",
    "ax[0].set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"r\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$\\Delta$M\",\n",
    "    # ylim=(1e-20, 1e-10),\n",
    ")\n",
    "# plot difference in the potential\n",
    "ax[1].plot(\n",
    "    r,\n",
    "    jnp.abs(\n",
    "        jax.vmap(Plummer_test._potential, in_axes=(0, None))(r, params)\n",
    "        - plum.potential(r)\n",
    "    ),\n",
    "    lw=lw,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax[1].set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"r\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$\\Delta \\Phi$\",\n",
    "    ylim=(1e-20, 1e-2),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It could be seen as annoying to have to physically vectorize functions, but it does give you a lot of control over how the functions are implemented and how they're used. If you wanted to see the potential for wide range of parameters you could also vectorize over that variable\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "params_list = [{\"M\": 1.0, \"rs\": 1.0}, {\"M\": 1.0, \"rs\": 2.0}, {\"M\": 1.0, \"rs\": 3.0}]\n",
    "params_dict = {k: jnp.array([p[k] for p in params_list]) for k in params_list[0]}\n",
    "\n",
    "vectorized_two = jax.vmap(\n",
    "    jax.vmap(Plummer_test._mass, in_axes=(0, None)),\n",
    "    in_axes=(None, 0),\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "test_vectorization = vectorized_two(r, params_dict)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(3, 100)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "test_vectorization.shape"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "for mass in test_vectorization:\n",
    "    ax.plot(r, mass)\n",
    "ax.set(xscale=\"log\", yscale=\"log\");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[None, None, Text(0.5, 0, 'r'), Text(0, 0.5, '$\\\\Phi$')]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 12,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "r = jnp.logspace(-12, 4)\n",
    "ax.plot(r, -jax.vmap(plum_test._potential, in_axes=(0, None))(r, params))\n",
    "ax.set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"r\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$\\Phi$\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "# ax.set(ylim=(1e-10, 1e-5));"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mathcal_E = jnp.logspace(-3, jnp.log10(-0.99 * plum_test._potential(1e-9, params)), 200)\n",
    "# r_e = plum_test.calculate_re(1, 1e5, params)\n",
    "r_e = plum_test.test_calculate_re(mathcal_E, params, rlim=1e10)\n",
    "# # print(r_e)\n",
    "# # print(mathcal_E)\n",
    "# # print(-plum_test._potential(1, params))\n",
    "# print(-plum_test._potential(r_e, params))\n",
    "# # r_e = jnp.logspace(-2, 2, 2000)\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(\n",
    "    r_e,\n",
    "    mathcal_E,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.plot(\n",
    "    r_e,\n",
    "    jnp.abs(jax.vmap(plum_test._potential, in_axes=(0, None))(r_e, params)),\n",
    "    linestyle=\"--\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=\"r\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$\\Phi$\",\n",
    "    # xlim=(1e-10, 1e-2),\n",
    ");"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "DF = plum_test.DistributionFunction(mathcal_E, params)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot(mathcal_E, DF, label=\"DynamicAll\", linestyle=\"-\", lw=3)\n",
    "ax.plot(mathcal_E, plum.DF(mathcal_E), label=\"plum\", linestyle=\"--\", lw=3)\n",
    "ax.set(\n",
    "    xscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    yscale=\"log\",\n",
    "    xlabel=r\"$\\mathcal{E}$\",\n",
    "    ylabel=r\"$f(\\mathcal{E})$\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Yay! We can accurately recover the analytical distribution function using the numerical methods."
   ]
  }
